      commentary: `The repetition of verse 48's teaching — no conventional means produces this vision — is deliberate. It frames the revelation of what does work, which comes in the next verse. The negative is stated before the positive: not Vedas, not austerity, not charity, not sacrifice. The usual toolkit of religious achievement is set aside entirely.\n\nThis teaching does not dismiss these practices. Each has real value within its proper domain. But none of them, individually or combined, is the path to the most direct encounter with the divine. They prepare; they purify; they develop the instrument. But the actual revelation requires something different — something that cannot be achieved but only received.\n\nThe framework being established here — conventional religious means are insufficient for the highest encounter — is the preparation for the next two verses, which name what is sufficient. The chapter is building toward its final teaching, and the negations are clearing the space for the one affirmation that matters most.`
