      commentary: `Bhaktyā ananyayā — by undivided devotion. After all the negations, this one affirmation. Not Vedas, not austerity, not ritual, not charity — but devotion, and specifically ananyayā: undivided, exclusive, without turning to another. This is the only door to the highest encounter with the divine.\n\nThree things are possible through this devotion: jñātum (to truly know), draṣṭum tattvena (to see in reality), and praveṣṭum (to enter into). These are three stages of the same journey: knowing, seeing, and being absorbed. Not just understanding about the divine, not just beholding the divine from outside, but entering — union, the dissolution of the separation between the devotee and the divine that bhakti was always reaching toward.\n\nAnanyayā — the operative word. Not devotion in the ordinary sense of religious practice, but devotion so complete that no other orientation competes with it. The mind that cannot be distracted from its beloved. The heart that has found its deepest object and does not look away. This is what makes knowledge, vision, and entry possible: the singular orientation that, when sustained, dissolves the apparent distance between the finite and the infinite.`
