      commentary: `The final verse of Chapter 11 is the summary of everything. After the cosmic vision, after the terror and wonder and the return to the human form — five qualities are named as the path to the divine: acting for the divine's sake, holding the divine as the supreme goal, devotion, freedom from attachment, and absence of enmity toward all beings.\n\nNirvairaḥ sarva-bhūteṣu — without enmity toward all beings. This final quality is the ethical ground of the entire teaching: the one who has seen the cosmic form, who has seen all beings within the divine body, cannot harbor enmity toward any of them. Having seen the enemy armies entering the same divine mouths as one's own warriors, having seen every category of being gazing in wonder at the same cosmic form — the ordinary distinctions of friend and enemy, us and them, dissolve.\n\nSa mām eti — that person comes to me. Not: that person attains a better life, or a heavenly reward, or spiritual powers. That person comes to me. The destination is the divine itself — not the divine's gifts but the divine's presence, not liberation from life but liberation into the source of life. This is where the Gita's entire teaching has been pointing since the first chapter.`
